'''William P. Byers''' (born 1943) is a [[Canadian]] mathematician and philosopher; professor emeritus in mathematics and statistics at [[Concordia University (Quebec)|Concordia University]] in [[Montreal|Montreal, Quebec]], Canada.

He completed a BSc ('64), and an MSc ('65) from [[McGill University]], and obtained his PhD ('69) from the [[University of California, Berkeley]].

His area of interests include Dynamical Systems, and the Philosophy of Mathematics.

Byers has published in various mathematical journals and published some books. ''[[How Mathematicians Think]]''<ref name="Chaitin">{{cite news|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg19526142.100-review-how-mathematicians-think-by-william-byers.html|title=Review: ''How Mathematicians Think'' by William Byers|last=Chaitin|first=Gregory|work=[[New Scientist]]|publisher=25 July 2007|accessdate=17 March 2012}}</ref> and ''The Blind Spot'', were both published by [[Princeton University Press]].
Byers' latest book, "Deep Thinking" <ref>{{cite web|title=Deep Thinking|url=http://www.worldscientific.com/worldscibooks/10.1142/9247|website=World Scientific|publisher=World Scientific|accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref> was published by World Scientific Publishing.

